  "prompt": "Do the prime minister of our country require visa to visit any country?",
  "response": "Whether the **Prime Minister of your country** requires a visa to visit another country depends on several factors:\n\n1. **Reciprocal Agreements**: Many countries have diplomatic agreements that exempt heads of state, government officials, and other high-ranking individuals from visa requirements for official visits. These agreements are often based on reciprocity and diplomatic protocols.\n\n2. **Purpose of Visit**: Visa requirements may differ depending on whether the visit is **official** (state visit, diplomatic mission) or **private**. Even if a visa is not required for official visits, it might still be necessary for private travel.\n\n3. **Bilateral Relations**: The relationship between your country and the destination country plays a significant role. Friendly bilateral ties often lead to visa exemptions for officials.\n\n4. **Destination Country's Policy**: Each country has its own rules regarding visa requirements, even for heads of state or government. Some countries may issue special diplomatic visas or waivers for such visits.\n\n5. **International Protocols**: Diplomatic immunity and international norms often ensure that high-ranking officials like prime ministers can travel without hindrance for official purposes.\n\nIn most cases, the Prime Minister would not require a standard visa for official visits, as diplomatic channels and protocols are used to facilitate such travel. However, for detailed information, it\u2019s best to consult the **Ministry of Foreign Affairs** or equivalent authority in your country.",
